{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536215"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:04:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:04:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15715"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.54,0.21,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103401"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8406"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85823"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3341"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4027"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32617"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32621"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103401"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with rapid onset confusion, severe agitation, and muscle rigidity. She has metastatic breast cancer and recently received news of disease progression on imaging eight weeks ago. She commenced sertraline 50 mg daily at that time for depression and increased her dose to 100mg. Her other medical history includes hypertension. Her medications include sertraline, anastrozole, amlodipine, and as-needed oxycodone. She lives at home with her partner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears severely agitated and delirious. Her pulse rate is 145/min, blood pressure 185/105 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 41.5\u00b0C. She has generalised muscle rigidity with sustained ankle clonus and markedly increased deep tendon reflexes. Her skin is diaphoretic and hot. She is becoming increasingly difficult to assess due to severe agitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatine kinase: 15,000 U/L (20-200)\u003Cbr /\u003ESodium: 145 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EPotassium: 5.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine: 180 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003Cbr /\u003EArterial blood gas shows metabolic acidosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll of her current medications are being discontinued at present including her sertraline.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous fluids","Rapid cooling measures","Cyproheptadine","Request urgent CT brain","Activated charcoal"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe serotonin syndrome, characterised by extreme hyperthermia (\u0026gt;41.1\u00b0C), severe muscle rigidity, and evidence of organ dysfunction (acute kidney injury, metabolic acidosis). This represents a medical emergency with significant risk of death if not treated promptly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid cooling measures\u003C/strong\u003E are the most appropriate first step in management. With a temperature of 41.5\u00b0C, immediate cooling is critical to prevent complications such as disseminated intravascular coagulation, multi-organ failure, and death. Cooling methods should include ice packs, cooling blankets, and cold intravenous fluids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fluids\u003C/strong\u003E are essential but should be implemented alongside cooling measures. The marked elevation in creatine kinase indicates severe rhabdomyolysis, which requires aggressive fluid resuscitation to prevent acute kidney injury. Given this is also encompassed in rapid cooling measures, this option is not the most appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECyproheptadine\u003C/strong\u003E is a 5-HT2A receptor antagonist which can be used in cases of serotonin syndrome, but cooling and stabilisation take precedence. It can be administered once initial cooling measures are underway, and its peak effect is in 6-9 hours after administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT brain\u003C/strong\u003E would delay critical interventions in a patient with clear signs of severe serotonin syndrome requiring immediate treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivated charcoal\u003C/strong\u003E would not be helpful as the sertraline was started weeks ago, and gastrointestinal decontamination would not affect current serotonin levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating cooling measures, management should include benzodiazepines for agitation and muscle rigidity, continued fluid resuscitation, and close monitoring in an intensive care setting. The severe hyperthermia, organ dysfunction, and metabolic derangements require immediate aggressive intervention to prevent mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn patients with hyperthermia, muscle rigidity and agitation on antipsychotics, Neuroleptic Malignant Syndrome (NMS) should be considered. However, in this case, her only listed significant medication is sertraline and this is far less likely to cause NMS than dopaminergic drugs, thus making serotonin syndrome far more likely. The presence of hyperreflexia and clonus also help to differentiate this clinically as NMS is often associated with suppressed reflexes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Severe serotonin syndrome is a medical emergency characterised by hyperthermia \u003E41.1\u00b0C, severe muscle rigidity, and organ dysfunction.","Immediate cooling measures and benzodiazepines are essential first-line interventions in severe serotonin syndrome.","Cyproheptadine is indicated in severe cases but should not delay other critical interventions."],"references":["Spadaro A, Scott KR, Koyfman A, Long B. High risk and low prevalence diseases: Serotonin syndrome. The American Journal of Emergency Medicine. 2022 Nov 1;61:90-7. Available online at ; https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0735675722005307","Chiew AL, Isbister GK. Management of serotonin syndrome (toxicity). British Journal of Clinical Pharmacology. 2024 Jun 26. Available online at ; https://bpspubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/pdf/10.1111/bcp.16152","Johnson O. Serotonin syndrome and neuroleptic malignant syndrome [Internet]. Deranged Physiology. 2019 [cited 2025 May 22]. Available from: https://derangedphysiology.com/main/required-reading/environmental-injuries-and-toxicology/Chapter-532/serotonin-syndrome-and-neuroleptic-malignant-syndrome"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85823"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15715"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85823"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-22T12:15:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-22T12:16:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8406"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103401"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https:/